:"Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire , England":"Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Saffron Walden, Essex, England":"Saffron Walden, Essex, England"},"en":{"1524–1545":"1524–1545","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1542–Female":"1542–Deceased","1543–Male":"1543–Deceased","1544–Male":"1544–Deceased","1545–1600":"1545–1600","1500–Male":"1500–Deceased","1500–Female":"1500–Deceased","1525":"1525","1524":"1524","1545":"1545","1600":"1600","April 1542":"April 1542","1544":"1544","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1542":"1542","1541":"1541","Woodborough, Nottinghamshire, England":"Woodborough, Nottinghamshire, England","Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire,England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire , England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Saffron Walden, Essex, England":"Saffron Walden, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lees","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name from Middle English <i>lees</i> ‘fields, arable land’, plural of <i>lee</i> (see   Lee  ), or from Middle English <i>lese</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ (Old English <i>lǣs</i>).","English: habitational name fromLeece or Lees in Lancashire, or Leese in Cheshire, all named from OldEnglish <i>lēas</i> ‘woodland clearings’ (plural of<i>lēah</i>), or from Leece in Cumbria, which was probably namedwith a Celtic word, <i>lïss</i> ‘hall, court, the principalhouse in a district’.","English: variant of   Leece   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Leece","meanings":["English: from a medieval female personal name, <i>Lece</i>, a short form of <i>Lettice</i> (from Latin <i>Laetitia</i>, meaning ‘happiness, gaiety’).","English: variant of   Lees  .","Irish: shortened form of Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Íosa</i>, Manx <i>Mac Guilley Yeesey</i> ‘son of <i>Giolla Íosa</i> (devotee or servant of Jesus)’. Ballaleece (‘Leece's farm’) in Kirk German was the family's main seat."]},{"name":"Leason","meanings":["English: metronymic from   Lees   3."]},{"name":"Lee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sang, Jae, Jong, Jung, Sung, Yong, Kyung, Seung, Dong, Kwang, Myung.","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a meadow or a patch of arable land, Middle English <i>lee</i>, <i>lea</i>, from Old English <i>lēa</i>, dative case (used after a preposition) of <i>lēah</i>, which originally meant ‘wood or glade’.","English: habitational name from any of the many places in England named with Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade’, including Lee in Buckinghamshire, Essex, Hampshire, Kent, and Shropshire, and Lea in Cheshire, Derbyshire, Herefordshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, and Wiltshire."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Baker","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Young camel’.  Abu-Bakr al-Ṣiddīq  (  573–634 ) was the Prophet's successor and the first rightly guided caliph (  632–4 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Baker Lees was born in 1524, in Woodborough, Nottinghamshire, England, his father, William Lees Sr, was 24 and his mother, Susanna Maelcot, was 24. He married Mary Thornleigh in 1541. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He lived in Warwickshire, England in 1524 and Saffron Walden, Essex, England in 1545. He died in 1545, in Woodborough, Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1524–1545":"1524–1545","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1542–Female":"1542–Surnud","1543–Male":"1543–Surnud","1544–Male":"1544–Surnud","1545–1600":"1545–1600","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1525":"1525","1524":"1524","1545":"1545","1600":"1600","April 1542":"aprill 1542","1544":"1544","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1542":"1542","1541":"1541","Woodborough, Nottinghamshire, England":"Woodborough, Nottinghamshire, England","Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire,England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire , England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saffron Walden, Essex, England":"Saffron Walden, Essex, England"},"fi":{"1524–1545":"1524–1545","1525–1600":"1525–1600","1542–Female":"1542–Kuollut","1543–Male":"1543–Kuollut","1544–Male":"1544–Kuollut","1545–1600":"1545–1600","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1500–Female":"1500–Kuollut","1525":"1525","1524":"1524","1545":"1545","1600":"1600","April 1542":"huhtikuu 1542","1544":"1544","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1542":"1542","1541":"1541","Woodborough, Nottinghamshire, England":"Woodborough, Nottinghamshire, England","Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England":"Tanworth in Arden, Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire,England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Warwickshire , England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Saffron Walden, Essex, England":"Saffron Walden, Essex, England"},"fr":{"1524–1545":"1524–1545","15